Speaker 1: This is one of the fundamental divides between what we mean when we talk about power saving modes.

584
00:37:35,420 --> 00:37:40,360
Speaker 1: If a thing is intended to always be plugged into power, power saving modes are there to protect the environment.

585
00:37:41,401 --> 00:37:48,140
Speaker 1: If your device is using a battery, power saving modes are intended to deal with the fact that battery technology has not kept up with society.

586
00:37:49,687 --> 00:37:52,600
Speaker 1: And they are radically different problem spaces.

587
00:37:54,202 --> 00:37:59,420
Speaker 1: And one of the reasons why they're so radically different is that batteries have yet another problem.

588
00:38:00,080 --> 00:38:10,840
Speaker 1: Depending on how you charge and drain the battery, you can have a device that performs better or saves power in the short term, but physically destroys the battery itself faster.

589
00:38:11,922 --> 00:38:15,840
Speaker 1: And those things are all configurable in phones now and configurable laptops now.

590
00:38:16,504 --> 00:38:19,040
Speaker 1: And they're too complicated for most people to understand and use.

591
00:38:19,480 --> 00:38:22,673
Speaker 0: You got to think about other devices too, not even computational devices.

592
00:38:22,854 --> 00:38:24,139
Speaker 0: Say like, I don't know.

593
00:38:24,460 --> 00:38:26,168
Speaker 1: A bike computer, I guess doesn't matter.

