00:40:34,060 --> 00:40:36,126
Speaker 0: The other thing you got to think about is like a television, right?

630
00:40:36,347 --> 00:40:40,900
Speaker 0: Even if you have a television that's not a smart TV, just an old regular flat screen TV, right?

631
00:40:41,420 --> 00:40:42,342
Speaker 0: Or even a CRT.

632
00:40:42,683 --> 00:40:51,660
Speaker 0: If it has a remote control, that TV is always drawing power because the IR receiver needs to be powered in order to know when you push the power button on the remote control.

633
00:40:51,980 --> 00:40:56,587
Speaker 1: Unless you have a TV old enough to have a physical wired remote, which I did have.

634
00:40:57,148 --> 00:41:05,760
Speaker 0: Another thing that you don't think about is that TVs, you expect when you push the power button for that TV to turn the fuck right on.

635
00:41:06,360 --> 00:41:08,668
Speaker 0: You don't want to be like push power button, wait, wait, wait.

636
00:41:08,728 --> 00:41:12,380
Speaker 1: Well, I'm already like, I push power button, my TV takes like seven seconds to boot.

637
00:41:13,820 --> 00:41:15,603
Speaker 1: It's not even a smart TV, it's just shitty.

638
00:41:15,623 --> 00:41:17,386
Speaker 0: The point is you want it to go fast, right?

639
00:41:17,746 --> 00:41:24,056
Speaker 0: But the TV has inside of it these capacitors that need to be filled up in order for the TV to turn on.

640
00:41:24,076 --> 00:41:26,340
Speaker 1: Not as much as old CRT TVs.

641
00:41:26,620 --> 00:41:29,024
Speaker 0: It's gotten better, but there's still some in there, right?

642
00:41:29,284 --> 00:41:33,851
Speaker 0: If you unplug your TV from the wall, those capacitors will slowly drain.

643
00:41:33,871 --> 00:41:39,320
Speaker 0: and then if you plug your TV back in, they'll slowly fill up as soon as you plug the TV back in.

644
00:41:39,701 --> 00:41:44,809
Speaker 0: If you unplug the TV, wait a long time for them to drain or dangerously drain them, do not do that.

645
00:41:46,211 --> 00:41:51,480
Speaker 0: And then plug the TV back in and push the power button, the TV might have some trouble turning on if you do that.

646
00:41:51,740 --> 00:42:05,818
Speaker 0: And the thing is, that slow drain, even though it might be ridiculously slow, it's still greater than zero, the power that is constantly trickling to keep them always full.

647
00:42:06,138 --> 00:42:07,660
Speaker 0: for that moment you push the power button.

648
00:42:09,781 --> 00:42:10,822
Speaker 1: So where are we going with all this?

649
00:42:11,123 --> 00:42:20,416
Speaker 1: The progression, I think, the problem with PCs is that the model and how power saving is done is so inconsistent and so shitty and so poorly documented.

650
00:42:20,756 --> 00:42:23,420
