652
00:42:30,072 --> 00:42:31,895
Speaker 0: Even then, I doubt it will always work perfectly.

653
00:42:32,256 --> 00:42:33,658
Speaker 0: You'll be like, sleep in it, it won't.

654
00:42:33,919 --> 00:42:34,600
Speaker 0: Or hibernate, it won't.

655
00:42:34,720 --> 00:42:46,360
Speaker 1: And phones have gone a different route in the sense that because the phones are a little bit more proprietary and self-contained, like I've watched this progression on Android, I can't speak to iPhone, where originally my Android phones would just, they used power at the rate they used it.

656
00:42:46,380 --> 00:42:47,221
Speaker 1: You want to use less power?

657
00:42:47,261 --> 00:42:50,385
Speaker 1: Just dim the screen, put it in airplane mode.

658
00:42:50,806 --> 00:43:02,160
Speaker 1: But over time, Android started adding all these features, like I could configure power saving things, but then it evolved to, it just made a bunch of automatic intelligent defaults about power saving.

659
00:43:02,661 --> 00:43:06,209
Speaker 1: And then it moved into even more advanced intelligent defaults.

660
00:43:06,229 --> 00:43:11,300
Speaker 1: So now my phone automatically, and I could configure this, but I don't need to, I don't care that much.

661
00:43:11,621 --> 00:43:20,300
Speaker 1: If it hits like 15% battery, it just automatically suspends as much as it can to save as much battery as possible without preventing basic things from working.

662
00:43:20,900 --> 00:43:27,510
Speaker 1: And then I can choose, whenever that happens, a button pops up and I can go in and hit the button and say, no, no, no, save as much battery as possible.

663
00:43:27,851 --> 00:43:33,520
Speaker 1: And then it'll just turn off way more stuff to save the battery as much as physically possible.

664
00:43:34,260 --> 00:43:44,656
Speaker 1: And by removing the complexity and just making it work with intelligent defaults, my phone just lasts a lot longer and no one has to learn a bunch of ACPI type nonsense.

